column11: Tesla’s new Model 3, its most affordable car model, is targeted at the mass market (Tesla, Fortune). With more than 400,000 Model 3 reservations on the books, Tesla aims to ramp up production quickly, with a stated goal of delivering 100,000-200,000 Model 3s in the second half of 2017 (Teslarati). Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

At the shareholder meeting yesterday, Musk said Tesla is producing 3,500 Model 3’s a week and he expects that number to reach 5,000 cars per week by the end of the month. (But he's said this before). Musk said manufacturing will be Tesla’s greatest strength long-term and predicted the company would be profitable in Q3 and Q4.

Monthly scorecard from InsideEVs is out [1], and has Model 3 Q2 sales at 10,125. Even if we assume this estimate is way off and increase it by 50%, that still only brings us to 25,140 overall historical sales. Tesla absolutely cannot deliver 25k cars in one month.
Bloomberg's tracker, as of May 30, is 32,501 produced and averaging 1,489 per week.

"Cars"? "deliver"? "customers"? These concepts--like, come to think of it, "before"--are not relevant to The Big Kahuna at Tesla. Implementing them, or even learning about them, would interfere with his widely admired business model: imagining and then announcing and then raking in the dough.

Tesla is currently estimated to be manufacturing 1,052 Tesla's a week (per Bloomberg VIN forecasting) up from 300 a week on Jan 1. At a lognormal growth distribution rate, Tesla should produce ~500 - 2000 vehicles per week by March/April. Assuming 2,000 vehicles a week for Q2, gives us 24,000 vehicles (2,000/week * 12) + 6,000 - 10,000 for Q1 equals 30-34k Model 3 Tesla delivers. There is the probably that Tesla outperforms and produces 3-4k vehicles in Q2 (90th percentile+).
Tesla plans to produce 5000 units per week by summer. Given Tesla's track record I highly doubt that they actually come close to that number by the end of the year.

Production has hit about 1000 units per week in January 2018. The Model 3 projected production is 20,000 per month under ideal conditions. The Model T had a five year ramp up from about 19,000 in 1910 to 260,000 in 1914. On a very rapid learning curve, the ramping up of Model 3 production numbers could exceed last year in the first half of this year. However, the Model T was roughly doubling every year during from 1910-1913. Less than 50,000 (Model 3) is likely in the first half of this year.
To reach 50,000 vehicles, they need to grow production about 35% or so per months, reaching 5000 per week at the end of Q2. That still seems doable, though a bit optimistic.
